# [WIMSE](../wg/wimse.html)

## Summary
The WIMSE working group met at IETF 125 to discuss the progress of its seven active chartered drafts. The chairs (Justin Richer and Pieter Kasselman) emphasized a "focus on finishing" existing work before adopting new items. Key activities included reviewing the status of the recently split workload credential documents, refining architecture definitions (specifically "workload instance"), and preparing [draft-ietf-wimse-workload-identity-practices](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-workload-identity-practices/) for completion.

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. Welcome and Chair Updates
*   **Presenters:** Justin Richer and Pieter Kasselman
*   **Slides:** [Welcome and Chair Updates](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-wimse-welcome-and-chair-updates-01)
*   The chairs noted the working group is at the two-year mark and needs to prioritize delivering the seven active drafts.
*   Four drafts were recently split from the original service-to-service authentication work to allow independent progression.

### 2. WIMSE Workload Credentials
*   **Presenter:** Brian Campbell
*   **Slides:** [WIMSE Workload Credentials](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-wimse-wimse-workload-credentials-00)
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-wimse-workload-creds](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-workload-creds/)
*   The draft defines Workload Identity Tokens (JWT) and Workload Identity Credentials (X.509).
*   Content regarding identifiers was moved to [draft-ietf-wimse-identifier](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-identifier/).
*   **Discussion:** Kathleen Moriarty sought clarification on the definition of "credential." Brian Campbell clarified it refers to the public key pair and its binding to the workload identifier (e.g., in the SAN of a certificate or the subject of a JWT). 

### 3. WIMSE Workload Proof Token (WPT)
*   **Presenter:** Brian Campbell
*   **Slides:** [WIMSE Workload Proof Token](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-wimse-workload-proof-token-00)
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-wimse-wpt](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-wpt/)
*   **Updates:** Clarified JTI claim treatment, fixed discrepancies in example claims, and inlined ABNF for the header. Added security considerations regarding audience and next-hop intermediaries.
*   **Discussion:** Brian Campbell suggested using transaction tokens as examples for downstream communications. A placeholder remains for the "Other Token Hash" (OTH) format.

### 4. HTTP Signatures
*   **Presenter:** Joe Salowey
*   **Slides:** [HTTP Signatures](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-wimse-http-signatures-00)
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-wimse-http-signature](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-http-signature/)
*   **Updates:** Introduced a mechanism to ensure the "audience" is signed to prevent signature reuse.
*   **Discussion:** Brian Campbell expressed technical reservations about introducing a new HTTP header to address audience, suggesting it might be the "wrong approach at the wrong layer." Joe Salowey acknowledged the complexity of URL rewriting in different environments.

### 5. WIMSE Architecture
*   **Presenter:** Joe Salowey
*   **Slides:** [IETF 125 WIMSE Architecture](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-wimse-ietf-125-wimse-architecture-00) and [WIMSE Architecture (update)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-wimse-wimse-architecture-update-00)
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-wimse-arch](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-arch/)
*   **Updates:** Reached revision -07. Defined "Workload Instance" (single running instantiation) vs. "Workload" (executable software entity).
*   **Discussion:** Hank Birkholz questioned if platform capabilities should be part of the instance definition. Kathleen Moriarty and Yaroslav Rosomakho suggested keeping the definition abstract, noting that platform details can be handled via attestation or specific identity paths.

### 6. WIMSE Identifier
*   **Presenter:** Yaroslav Rosomakho
*   **Slides:** [WIMSE Identifier](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-wimse-wimse-identifier-00)
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-wimse-identifier](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-identifier/)
*   **Updates:** Defined "Workload Identifier Origin" (scheme + trust domain). Defined the `wimse:` URI scheme as a flexible fallback.
*   **Discussion:** 
    *   The authors currently see no need for a specific WIMSE identifier scheme registry.
    *   The group aims to keep the `wimse:` scheme flexible regarding path notation.
    *   The draft aims for Working Group Last Call (WGLC) by IETF 126.

### 7. WIMSE Workload Identity Practices
*   **Presenter:** Arndt Schwenkler
*   **Slides:** [WIMSE Workload Identity Practices](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-wimse-wimse-workload-identity-practices-00)
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-wimse-workload-identity-practices](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-workload-identity-practices/)
*   **Updates:** Currently in WGLC. Addressing reviews from Kathleen Moriarty and Joe Salowey regarding terminology (identity vs. credential) and federation.
*   **Discussion:** Differentiation between "access credentials" and "signed instance metadata" (common in cloud providers) will be further clarified.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **Credential/WPT/Signature alignment:** The editors of [draft-ietf-wimse-workload-creds](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-workload-creds/) must prioritize finalizing this document, as it is a prerequisite for [draft-ietf-wimse-wpt](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-wpt/) and [draft-ietf-wimse-http-signature](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-http-signature/).
*   **Acknowledgements:** Editors for all drafts are tasked with updating acknowledgement sections to credit contributors properly.
*   **Workload Identity Practices Review:** Fleming Lau Jensen, Kathleen Moriarty, Lucia Rodriguez, and Brian Campbell volunteered to provide final reviews once the next revision is published.

## Next Steps
*   Publish updated versions of [draft-ietf-wimse-arch](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-arch/) and [draft-ietf-wimse-identifier](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-identifier/) with the goal of reaching WGLC by IETF 126.
*   Chairs to re-issue WGLC for [draft-ietf-wimse-workload-identity-practices](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-wimse-workload-identity-practices/) following the next revision.
*   Consider an interim meeting specifically focused on aligning terminology across the entire document suite.